Scientists from the Center for Ice Hydrometeorological Information have prepared a brief overview of the current ice situation in the Arctic seas🧊🌊🔹In the Barents Sea, the edge of drifting ice has shifted south to 25 miles. The area of first-year medium ice to the west of the FZL archipelago has increased.🔹In the Pechora Sea, the edge of drifting ice has shifted south to 30 miles.🔹The amount of first-year medium ice has increased in the southwestern part of the Kara Sea.🔹In the eastern part of the Laptev Sea, thick first-year ice predominates, in the western - one-year average.🔹In the East Siberian Sea, in the northeastern and southwestern parts of it, the area of predominance of one-year thick ice has increased.🔹In the waters of the Chukchi Sea, the predominance of one-year average ice with inclusions of one-year thick ice remains;

